public class ID3v23FrameBody
extends ID3v23FrameBodyUtility

This is the base class for all ID3v2.3 frame bodies. Although ID3v2.3 defines 74 different types of frames, many groups of frame bodies have the same fields, and thus are implemented by a single class. For example, there are 38 text information frames, and thus the corresponding frame bodies are implemented in one ID3v23FrameBodyTextInformation class. Similarly, there are 8 url link frames, but all are implemented using the ID3v23FrameBodyURLLink class.

Each frame body has a raw, binary buffer, which is nothing more than a byte array. This is what is read in from the .mp3 file. This byte array holds all of the values for a given frame body. When a frame body is read in from an .mp3 file (more acurately, from the ID3v2.3 tag in the .mp3 file), this binary buffer is parsed and the values are stored in the frame body's data members. Users are then free to change the values of the frame body's data members. When the user is finished making changes, he must call the setBuffer() method in order to write all the frame body's data members back to the binary buffer, before calling save(FileOutputStream). However, you should not be invoking these methods, as calling MP3.save() will handle all of this for you.

Many of the ID3v2.3 frame bodies have the same fields. For example, many frame bodies have an encoding field, some have a language field, and others have a description field. Since Java does not permit multiple inheritance (like C++ for example), there were three options:

  1. copy and paste the code for each common field into all of the frame body classes in which they belonged.
  2. create a base class for every combination of fields and have the derived frame body classes singly inherit from the appropriate base class.
  3. place the common fields in a single base class even though not every derived class needs the common fields.

None of these choices were even close to being a good choice. There are very good reasons why each of these implementations is not only bad, but very bad. So, I had to pick the least bad one. That being the case, I found the third choice to be the best choice out of the three. Before you start firing off angry e-mails, let me explain a little. With the first solution, I would copy getEncoding() and setEncoding() methods 13 times into frame body classes that contained the encoding field. I would copy the getDescription() and setDescription() methods 8 times into frame body classes that contained the description field, and so on. Everyone knows why copying and pasting code is bad, but in case you don't, it means that if there was a bug in the setEncoding() method, I would have to go and fix it 13 times instead of just once. With choice 2, creating base classes for each combination of common fields would mean creating a lot of extra classes, and would be very messy in my opinion. This left me with the third choice, which was easy simple, easy to implement, easy to maintain, and avoided the problems of choices one and two. The problem with choice three is that now derived frame classes that happened not to have an encoding field or a description field, got one anyway. And again, this is very bad. But its not as bad as choices one and two. Even though a derived frame body class might have an encoding field which it didn't need, calling the getEncoding() or setEncoding() methods would have no effect on the actual frame body. The unused fields would not be saved in the frames that didn't need them, so the damage of derived frames having the extra unsed fields was minimal. And thus, choice three was chosen.

ID3 tag version 2.3.0 standard, wikipedia history of ID3 tags

setBuffer

public void setBuffer()
If the frame body's values have been modified, then resize the raw binary buffer and store the new values there. When finished, the dirty flag is reset to indicate that the buffer is up to date, and the frame is now ready to be saved to the .mp3 file.

this method should be abstract. However, the ID3v23Frame constructor needs to be able to instanitate instances of a frame body in the case where it encounters an invalid frame. For this reason, this method was made concrete and in this base class simply throws an exception if it is ever called. However, derived classes implement this method to correctly update the binary buffer.
